-- 01-research-plan-evolver-frames.cell (v0.2)
-- Execution trace of 01-research-plan-evolver.cell via eval-one
--
-- v0.2 execution notes:
--   - File-scope ⊨? active: retry max 3 with failure context, then ⊥
--   - ⊢⊢ spawn-experiments uses `replace` mode: spawned cells discarded between ⊢∘ iterations
--   - Wildcard deps re-resolve per iteration (v0.2 spec-compliant)
--
-- Problem: "Why do some open-source projects thrive while others with
-- similar quality die?"

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 0: evaluate problem (trivial pass-through)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { problem } — only cell with all givens bound
-- Blocked: { hypothesize } — needs problem→statement
-- Blocked: everything else — transitive

⊢ problem
  given statement ≡ "Why do some open-source projects thrive while others with similar quality die?"
  yield statement

-- eval-one: problem is a pass-through. statement is already bound via given ≡.
-- No ∴ body, no ⊢= body. Yield inherits from given.

  yield statement ≡ "Why do some open-source projects thrive while others with similar quality die?"

-- oracle check:
--   ⊨ statement is a clear research question → ✓

-- state after frame 0: problem frozen.
-- Ready set: { hypothesize }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 1: evaluate hypothesize (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { hypothesize }
-- Blocked: { design-experiments } — needs hypothesize→hypotheses

⊢ hypothesize
  given problem→statement ≡ "Why do some open-source projects thrive while others with similar quality die?"
  yield hypotheses[]

  ∴ Generate 3-5 distinct, testable hypotheses...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield hypotheses ≡ [
    "H1: Projects whose maintainer actively cultivates social presence (blog posts, conference talks, Twitter/Mastodon engagement) attract exponentially more contributors than technically superior but socially invisible projects, because visibility drives discovery and discovery drives contribution.",
    "H2: Projects adopted as transitive dependencies by popular frameworks experience a network-effect flywheel — each new dependent project brings new users who file issues and contribute patches — that sustains them regardless of intrinsic code quality.",
    "H3: Projects with low onboarding friction (documented build process, good-first-issue labels, CONTRIBUTING.md, fast CI) retain first-time contributors at 3-5x the rate of high-friction projects, and long-term contributor retention is the primary predictor of project survival.",
    "H4: Corporate-sponsored projects survive maintainer burnout because paid engineers bridge the gap during leadership transitions; volunteer-only projects die when the founder leaves regardless of community size or code quality.",
    "H5: Projects that occupy a unique niche (no close substitutes) survive longer than projects in crowded spaces, because users have no alternative and are forced to contribute fixes rather than switch."
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ length(hypotheses) ≥ 3 → ✓ (5 hypotheses)
--   ⊨ each hypothesis proposes a testable causal claim → ✓
--     H1: social presence → contributor growth (testable via social metrics)
--     H2: dependency adoption → growth flywheel (testable via package graph)
--     H3: onboarding friction → contributor retention (testable via repo metadata)
--     H4: corporate backing → burnout resilience (testable via funding data)
--     H5: niche uniqueness → survival (testable via competitor analysis)
--   ⊨ hypotheses are mutually distinct → ✓ (social, ecosystem, onboarding, funding, niche)

-- state after frame 1: hypothesize frozen.
-- Ready set: { design-experiments }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 2: evaluate design-experiments (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { design-experiments }
-- Blocked: { evaluate-feasibility } — needs design-experiments→experiments

⊢ design-experiments
  given hypothesize→hypotheses ≡ ["H1: Projects whose maintainer actively cultivates...", "H2: Projects adopted as transitive dependencies...", "H3: Projects with low onboarding friction...", "H4: Corporate-sponsored projects...", "H5: Projects that occupy a unique niche..."]
  yield experiments[]

  ∴ For each hypothesis, design one experiment...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield experiments ≡ [
    "E1 (tests H1): Sample 200 GitHub projects in the same domain (Python web frameworks) with similar star counts at year 1. Measure maintainer's social media presence (Mastodon/Twitter followers, blog posts/year, conference talks). Correlate social-engagement score with 5-year contributor growth rate. Outcome: r > 0.5 supports H1; r < 0.2 refutes it.",
    "E2 (tests H2): Using libraries.io dependency data, identify 50 projects adopted by a top-50 npm/PyPI package between 2018-2021. Compare their contributor and download trajectories against 50 matched controls (same language, similar initial stars, not adopted as dependency). Outcome: if adopted projects grow >2x faster over 3 years, supports H2.",
    "E3 (tests H3): Scrape 500 GitHub repos for CONTRIBUTING.md presence, good-first-issue labels, CI build time (from GitHub Actions), and README quality score. Track first-time contributor return rate (second contribution within 6 months). Regression: does onboarding friction score predict return rate controlling for project size? Outcome: if friction explains >30% of return-rate variance, supports H3.",
    "E4 (tests H4): Identify 100 projects whose primary maintainer went inactive (no commits for 6+ months). Split by funding status: corporate-backed (employer-sponsored commits), donation-funded (Open Collective/GitHub Sponsors), volunteer-only. Compare 2-year survival rate across groups. Outcome: if funded projects survive at >2x the rate, supports H4.",
    "E5 (tests H5): For 300 npm packages, compute a niche-uniqueness score: inverse of the number of packages with >50% keyword overlap. Correlate with 5-year survival. Control for download count and star count. Outcome: if niche-uniqueness independently predicts survival (β > 0.2, p < 0.05), supports H5."
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ length(experiments) = length(hypotheses) → ✓ (5 = 5)
--   ⊨ each experiment maps to exactly one hypothesis → ✓ (E1→H1, E2→H2, E3→H3, E4→H4, E5→H5)
--   ⊨ each experiment specifies measurable outcomes → ✓ (all have quantitative thresholds)

-- state after frame 2: design-experiments frozen.
-- Ready set: { evaluate-feasibility }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 3: evaluate evaluate-feasibility (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { evaluate-feasibility }
-- Blocked: { spawn-experiments } — needs feasible[], hypotheses

⊢ evaluate-feasibility
  given design-experiments→experiments ≡ ["E1...", "E2...", "E3...", "E4...", "E5..."]
  yield feasible[], infeasible[]

  ∴ Evaluate feasibility with publicly available data...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield feasible ≡ [
    "E2 (tests H2): libraries.io provides full dependency graphs via API. npm/PyPI download stats are public. GitHub contributor counts are API-accessible. Fully feasible.",
    "E3 (tests H3): CONTRIBUTING.md and issue labels are GitHub API fields. CI build time is approximable from Actions run durations. First-time contributor detection via commit author history. Feasible with minor approximation on CI timing.",
    "E4 (tests H4): Open Collective data is public. GitHub Sponsors is partially visible. Corporate backing detectable from commit email domains (@company.com). Maintainer departure detectable from commit gaps. Feasible with some manual validation for corporate status.",
    "E5 (tests H5): npm package keywords are available via the npm registry API. Keyword overlap is computable. Download counts and stars are public. Fully feasible."
  ]

  yield infeasible ≡ [
    "E1 (tests H1): Twitter/X API access is severely restricted since 2023 (prohibitive cost for academic use). Mastodon follower counts require per-instance API calls with inconsistent rate limits. Conference talk data has no central registry. Blog post counts require crawling personal sites. INFEASIBLE — social media data access is unreliable, fragmented, and expensive."
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ length(feasible) + length(infeasible) = 5 → ✓ (4 + 1 = 5)
--   ⊨ each feasible experiment uses publicly available data sources → ✓
--     E2: libraries.io API, npm/PyPI, GitHub API
--     E3: GitHub API, Actions logs
--     E4: Open Collective, GitHub Sponsors, commit emails
--     E5: npm registry API, GitHub API

-- state after frame 3: evaluate-feasibility frozen.
-- Ready set: { spawn-experiments }
-- NOTE: H1 (social presence) is orphaned — no feasible experiment. The ⊢∘ loop
--       should catch this and revise or drop H1 based on lack of evidence.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 4: evaluate spawn-experiments (⊢⊢ spawner fires, replace mode)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { spawn-experiments }
-- spawn-experiments is ⊢⊢ with `replace` — discards previous spawned cells on re-fire
-- This is iteration 1: no previous cells to discard.

⊢⊢ spawn-experiments
  given evaluate-feasibility→feasible ≡ ["E2...", "E3...", "E4...", "E5..."]
  given hypothesize→hypotheses ≡ ["H1...", "H2...", "H3...", "H4...", "H5..."]
  given §experiment-template
  yield §experiment-cells[]
  until length(experiment-cells) = 4
  max 5
  replace

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Spawner instantiates experiment-template 4 times, one per feasible experiment.

  yield experiment-cells ≡ [§experiment-0, §experiment-1, §experiment-2, §experiment-3]

-- oracle check:
--   ⊨ length(experiment-cells) = length(feasible) → ✓ (4 = 4)

-- SPAWNER EFFECT: 4 new cells enter the frontier:

⊢ experiment-0
  given hypothesis ≡ "H2: Projects adopted as transitive dependencies by popular frameworks experience a network-effect flywheel that sustains them regardless of intrinsic code quality."
  given experiment-desc ≡ "E2: Using libraries.io dependency data, identify 50 projects adopted by a top-50 npm/PyPI package between 2018-2021. Compare contributor and download trajectories against 50 matched controls."
  yield result, supports-hypothesis

  ∴ Simulate running «experiment-desc» to test «hypothesis».

  ⊨ result describes concrete findings
  ⊨ supports-hypothesis ∈ { "supports", "refutes", "inconclusive" }

⊢ experiment-1
  given hypothesis ≡ "H3: Projects with low onboarding friction retain first-time contributors at 3-5x the rate of high-friction projects, and contributor retention is the primary predictor of survival."
  given experiment-desc ≡ "E3: Scrape 500 GitHub repos for CONTRIBUTING.md, good-first-issue labels, CI build time. Track first-time contributor return rate within 6 months."
  yield result, supports-hypothesis

  ∴ Simulate running «experiment-desc» to test «hypothesis».

  ⊨ result describes concrete findings
  ⊨ supports-hypothesis ∈ { "supports", "refutes", "inconclusive" }

⊢ experiment-2
  given hypothesis ≡ "H4: Corporate-sponsored projects survive maintainer burnout because paid engineers bridge the gap during leadership transitions."
  given experiment-desc ≡ "E4: Identify 100 projects that lost their primary maintainer. Split by funding status. Compare 2-year survival rate."
  yield result, supports-hypothesis

  ∴ Simulate running «experiment-desc» to test «hypothesis».

  ⊨ result describes concrete findings
  ⊨ supports-hypothesis ∈ { "supports", "refutes", "inconclusive" }

⊢ experiment-3
  given hypothesis ≡ "H5: Projects that occupy a unique niche survive longer than those in crowded spaces because users must contribute fixes rather than switch."
  given experiment-desc ≡ "E5: Compute niche-uniqueness score (inverse keyword overlap) for 300 npm packages. Correlate with 5-year survival controlling for downloads and stars."
  yield result, supports-hypothesis

  ∴ Simulate running «experiment-desc» to test «hypothesis».

  ⊨ result describes concrete findings
  ⊨ supports-hypothesis ∈ { "supports", "refutes", "inconclusive" }

-- state after frame 4: spawn-experiments frozen, 4 new cells in frontier.
-- Ready set: { experiment-0, experiment-1, experiment-2, experiment-3 } — all ready
-- Blocked: { collect-results } — needs experiment-*→result (wildcard waits for ALL matches)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 5: evaluate experiment-0 (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { experiment-0, experiment-1, experiment-2, experiment-3 }
-- Pick: experiment-0 (arbitrary — confluence guarantees same final result)

⊢ experiment-0
  given hypothesis ≡ "H2: dependency flywheel..."
  given experiment-desc ≡ "E2: libraries.io dependency data..."
  yield result, supports-hypothesis

  ∴ Simulate running E2 to test H2...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield result ≡ "Analysis of 50 npm/PyPI packages adopted by top-50 frameworks between 2018-2021 vs 50 matched controls: adopted packages saw 3.8x median contributor growth over 3 years (p<0.001). Monthly downloads grew 7.2x vs 1.4x for controls. The flywheel effect is strongest in the first 12 months post-adoption (contributor influx peaks at 6 months). However, 7 of 50 adopted packages (14%) still declined or died — 4 were replaced by framework-native alternatives, 2 had critical security incidents that eroded trust, and 1 had a hostile maintainer fork. The flywheel is powerful but conditional: it requires the upstream framework to KEEP choosing you."

  yield supports-hypothesis ≡ "supports"

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ result describes concrete findings → ✓ (specific sample sizes, effect sizes, exceptions)
--   ⊨ supports-hypothesis ∈ { "supports", "refutes", "inconclusive" } → ✓

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 6: evaluate experiment-1 (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { experiment-1, experiment-2, experiment-3 }
-- Pick: experiment-1

⊢ experiment-1
  given hypothesis ≡ "H3: onboarding friction → retention..."
  given experiment-desc ≡ "E3: scrape repos, measure onboarding signals..."
  yield result, supports-hypothesis

  ∴ Simulate running E3 to test H3...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield result ≡ "Of 500 GitHub repos sampled across Python and JavaScript ecosystems: repos with CONTRIBUTING.md had 1.9x higher first-time contributor return rate. Repos with good-first-issue labels: 2.3x. Repos with both plus CI under 5 minutes: 3.1x. The combined onboarding friction score explained 24% of variance in return rate (R²=0.24, p<0.001). However, the 3-5x claim in H3 is only met by the top-decile onboarding-quality projects. More critically, contributor retention alone predicted project 5-year survival with only 0.43 AUC — barely above chance. Projects with excellent onboarding still died from maintainer burnout, ecosystem shifts, and funding collapse. Retention is necessary but insufficient."

  yield supports-hypothesis ≡ "inconclusive"

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ result describes concrete findings → ✓
--   ⊨ supports-hypothesis ∈ { "supports", "refutes", "inconclusive" } → ✓

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 7: evaluate experiment-2 (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { experiment-2, experiment-3 }
-- Pick: experiment-2

⊢ experiment-2
  given hypothesis ≡ "H4: corporate sponsors → burnout resilience..."
  given experiment-desc ≡ "E4: track maintainer departure, split by funding..."
  yield result, supports-hypothesis

  ∴ Simulate running E4 to test H4...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield result ≡ "Of 93 projects where the primary maintainer went inactive for 6+ months: corporate-backed projects (n=28) survived at 79% rate, donation-funded projects (n=22) at 59%, volunteer-only projects (n=43) at 28%. The corporate advantage is stark. However, causal direction is ambiguous: 18 of 28 corporate-backed projects were already widely used before receiving corporate support. A natural experiment subset — 11 projects that received their first corporate sponsor AFTER the maintainer departed — survived at 64%, suggesting funding does causally help but the effect is smaller than the cross-sectional comparison implies. The strongest predictor within the corporate-backed group was having ≥2 paid contributors (92% survival vs 58% with only 1)."

  yield supports-hypothesis ≡ "supports"

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ result describes concrete findings → ✓
--   ⊨ supports-hypothesis ∈ { "supports", "refutes", "inconclusive" } → ✓

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 8: evaluate experiment-3 (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { experiment-3 }
-- Pick: experiment-3

⊢ experiment-3
  given hypothesis ≡ "H5: niche uniqueness → survival..."
  given experiment-desc ≡ "E5: niche-uniqueness score for 300 npm packages..."
  yield result, supports-hypothesis

  ∴ Simulate running E5 to test H5...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield result ≡ "For 300 npm packages with ≥100 weekly downloads, the niche-uniqueness score (inverse keyword overlap with other packages) showed a weak but significant correlation with 5-year survival: β=0.14, p=0.02 in a model controlling for download count and star count. However, the effect disappears (β=0.03, p=0.58) when adding dependency PageRank to the model. Niche uniqueness appears to be a proxy for ecosystem position — unique packages tend to be depended upon because there's no alternative, and it's the dependency centrality (not the uniqueness itself) that drives survival. In the top quartile of niche-uniqueness, packages WITH high PageRank survived at 89% vs packages WITHOUT high PageRank at 41%. The niche effect is almost entirely mediated by dependency graph position."

  yield supports-hypothesis ≡ "refutes"

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ result describes concrete findings → ✓
--   ⊨ supports-hypothesis ∈ { "supports", "refutes", "inconclusive" } → ✓

