-- LLM evaluation:

  yield experiments ≡ [
    "E2' (tests H2'): Identify packages that were DROPPED by their upstream framework (e.g., moment.js by Angular/React recommendations shifting to alternatives). Track contributor trajectory for 18 months post-drop. Measure whether projects with intrinsic utility (used directly, not just transitively) survive the drop better. Outcome: if >60% lose majority of contributors within 18 months, supports the conditional/fragile claim in H2'.",
    "E3' (tests H3'): Test the hygiene-factor framing. Among projects that died, compare their onboarding quality against projects that survived. If dead projects have significantly WORSE onboarding, it's a hygiene factor. If dead and surviving projects have similar onboarding quality, onboarding is irrelevant. Control for project age and ecosystem.",
    "E4' (tests H4'): Focus on the ≥2 paid contributor threshold. For 50 corporate-backed projects, compare survival rates at different paid-engineer counts (1, 2, 3+). If there's a step-function at 2, supports the specific threshold claim. Also: compare projects where corporate funding was withdrawn vs maintained.",
    "E6 (tests H6): Compute dependency PageRank for 1000 npm packages. Model 5-year survival as a function of PageRank, controlling for: download count, star count, contributor count, corporate backing, and onboarding quality. Outcome: if PageRank remains the strongest individual predictor after controlling for all other factors, H6 is the dominant theory."
  ]

