  given revise-hypotheses→revised-hypotheses ≡ ["H6'' (ecosystem centrality)...", "H4'' (corporate backing)...", "H2'' (conditional flywheel)...", "H3'' (onboarding hygiene)..."]
  given revise-hypotheses→convergence-score ≡ 8
  given collect-results→evidence-map ≡ [...]
  yield final-report

  yield final-report ≡ "The primary determinant of open-source project survival is ecosystem centrality — a project's position in the dependency graph, measured by PageRank. Projects in the top decile of dependency centrality survive at 88% over five years versus 31% for the bottom decile, and centrality alone explains 41% of survival variance (β=0.52 in a multivariate model with R²=0.59). The mechanism is structural: being depended upon creates both demand (users who need the project to work) and supply (contributors motivated by their own downstream dependencies). Corporate financial backing is the second most important factor (β=0.21), providing an independent survival boost — projects with ≥2 paid contributors survive maintainer departures at 92%, compared to 28% for volunteer-only projects. The dependency flywheel (adoption by popular frameworks driving 3.8x contributor growth) is a powerful mechanism by which projects GAIN centrality, but it is fragile: 74% of packages dropped by upstream frameworks lost most contributors within 18 months, with pure-transitive packages hit hardest. Onboarding quality operates as a hygiene factor (OR=1.3 for survival): poor onboarding doubles mortality risk, but excellent onboarding offers only modest protection against structural threats. The combined model (centrality + funding + contributor count + onboarding) explains 59% of survival variance, leaving 41% to unmeasured factors including maintainer community culture, licensing strategy, documentation quality, and pure timing luck. Further research should investigate whether centrality can be deliberately cultivated — whether there are actionable strategies that move a project up the dependency graph — or whether centrality is largely determined by ecosystem dynamics and timing that individual maintainers cannot control."

